<!--Temple and Shrine Powers--><!--Temple and Shrine Powers--><!--Temple and Shrine Powers--><!--Temple and Shrine Powers--><!--Temple and Shrine Powers--><!--Temple and Shrine Powers-->

'''Jisha Seiryoku''' (寺社勢力) refers to the religious and temple powers of Japan, also known as '''Shaji Seiryoku''' (社寺勢力).<ref>[[Hiraizumi Kiyomi]] used the term "Shaji" and "Shaji Seiryoku" in his work *The Relationship Between Temples and Society in the Middle Ages* (1926).</ref> These powers were significant during Japan's {{ill|medieval period|ja|日本の中世|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/medieval period|qq=}}, sharing authority with the {{ill|Bakufu|ja|武家政権|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bakufu|qq=}} and the {{ill|Imperial Court of Japan|ja|朝廷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Court of Japan|qq=}}. Unlike centralized political entities, the religious powers were decentralized, with each temple or shrine acting independently. Even within a single temple or shrine, various factions often vied for dominance, which is why the term "seiryoku" (power) is used.

== Overview ==
During the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}}, major temples such as {{ill|Enryaku-ji|ja|延暦寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enryaku-ji|qq=}} and {{ill|Kōfuku-ji|ja|興福寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōfuku-ji|qq=}} established their own military forces, including {{ill|Sohei|ja|僧兵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sohei|qq=}} (warrior monks), and utilized demonstrations such as carrying {{ill|Mikoshi|ja|神輿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikoshi|qq=}} in {{ill|Goso|ja|強訴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Goso|qq=}} to assert their demands.

Temples also maintained large entourages of lay followers known as {{ill|Shuto|ja|衆徒|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shuto|qq=}} and {{ill|Shinto|ja|神人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto|qq=}}, enabling significant economic, academic, and artistic activities. The areas surrounding these temples, now recognized as {{ill|Temple Precinct Cities|ja|境内都市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Temple complexes as urban areas|qq=}}, functioned as proto-megalopolises.

{{ill|Enryaku-ji|ja|延暦寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enryaku-ji|qq=}} and its subordinate shrine, {{ill|Yasaka Shrine|lt=Yasaka Shrine|lt=Gion-sha|ja|祇園社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion-sha|qq=}} (modern {{ill|Yasaka Shrine|ja|八坂神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yasaka Shrine|qq=}}), dominated eastern Kyoto, while {{ill|Kōfuku-ji|ja|興福寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōfuku-ji|qq=}} controlled nearly all of Yamato Province’s estates. These two powerful entities were collectively known as the "Nanto-Hokurei" (南都北嶺).

Within the temple domains, the {{ill|Right of asylum|ja|アジール権|fr|Droit d'asile|ja|アジール|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Right of asylum|qq=}} regions attracted impoverished civilians and marginalized individuals. Temples also provided refuge to fugitives, such as {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshitsune|ja|源義経|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoshitsune|qq=}} and {{ill|Emperor Go-Daigo|ja|後醍醐天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Go-Daigo|qq=}}, as government authority was limited within these areas due to rights like {{ill|Kendan-funyu|ja|検断不入|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kendan-funyu|qq=}}.

During the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|qq=}}, leaders like {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oda Nobunaga|qq=}} and {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyotomi Hideyoshi|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=}} clashed with temple powers. Despite their opposition, they utilized temple resources, such as Enryaku-ji craftsmen for building {{ill|Azuchi Castle|ja|安土城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Azuchi Castle|qq=}} and {{ill|Negoro-ji|ja|根来寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Negoro-ji|qq=}} firearms for military campaigns.

Hideyoshi's 1585–1588 {{ill|Sword Hunt|ja|刀狩令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sword Hunt|qq=}} included the disarmament of temple forces, effectively ending the five-century-long dominance of Jisha Seiryoku within Japan's power structures.

